Q4 is 1.16. Increase the past 4 qtrs has been +.14, +.10, +.09, +.15. A similar rate of increase would result in a range of 1.25-1.31%. The max increase in 1 qtr was during the 2008 financial crisis, +1.26, resulting in a ceiling of 2.42. The difference between now and 2008 is the uneven nature of the distress right now. This is NOT a liquidity crisis. Lodging is hurting badly, retail and office less so. But other types of commercial real estate, such as warehousing and industrial, are not hurting at all. Additionally, there's so much extra capital/liquidity floating around right now that investors are anxious to either purchase properties outright from delinquent owners, or to refinance or otherwise shore up/profit from the distressed owners. Furthermore, banks (themselves flush with liquidity) are also willing to negotiate with mortgagees, knowing that some sort of payment is better than no payment (witness last year's Mall of America massive renegotiation). All of this collectively is keeping loan delinquencies low. The excess liquidity and lopsided real estate "pain" make this a very unusual "recession." All of these factors lead me to believe that even with the "main street" economy worsening, this rate is highly likely to stay below 2% this quarter. Reference website: FRED graphs/data at link above.

Looking at CMBS pricing as a proxy for CRE risk: CMBS ETF is up 5% YTD, compared with 10% for similar duration treasuries. So the spread component (extra yield above treasuries) is out 5%. Assume that half of that is a risk premium, and half of that is due to default risk. So 2.5% is due to default risk, and if you assume a recovery rate of 50% that means a 5% default cycle over the life of the CMBS. The big question is how much you get and when.

While continued rise in CMBS delinquency seems unescapable, the issue is timing: lenders forbearance, US government stimulus delays the peak of delinquencies. So far given the magnitude of the crisis, delinquency rate increase is small: 1.00 in Q3 vs. 0.92 in Q2. We have three quarter before the end of this question. The increase in delinquency rates is very likely to be non-linear, so I not counting on continued 10bps increase over the next 3 qtr.
